    "description": "Sijilmasa was a sizeable and wealthy urban center in its heyday. The Andalusian historian and geographer Abu ‘Ubayd al-Bakri (d. 1094) described the city as, “a wall with twelve gates. Within are beautiful houses, many having gardens, magnificent public buildings, a mosque that is solidly built, and baths that are poorly built.\" This fragment of painted plaster, bearing an inscription from the Qur’an, was found at the site of an elite residence of the 9th or 10th century. Just a century or two later of a mosque was built on the same location. The carved stucco fragment with geometric patterns was part of the decorative program of the mosque during the imperial regimes of the Almoravids or Almohads, both with local Amazigh (Berber) origins.",
